WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:24.860
﻿Plasma Youth Sports Games
with Unsuccess of the champion,

00:00:24.955 --> 00:00:27.715
would like to thank Slaven Bilić
for stepping in as the host.

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:31.309
Bilić is one of the first sponsors,
ambassador and is our biggest promoter.

00:00:31.431 --> 00:00:34.409
He used his life and sports experience
in order to prepare high-quality content

00:00:34.664 --> 00:00:37.184
with his guests for all generations.
Thanks, Nane!

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:43.940
We said...

00:00:44.900 --> 00:00:48.460
You said that one of the reasons
was that your father

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:53.180
devoted more time to Ivica,
and you probably got fed up.

00:00:53.380 --> 00:00:55.060
Is it...

00:00:55.320 --> 00:00:58.092
Both you and Blanka Vlašić
had thyroid surgery,

00:00:58.256 --> 00:01:01.101
and it can often cause problems
because of too much stress.

00:01:01.308 --> 00:01:02.588
Is that...

00:01:02.773 --> 00:01:08.365
And it seemed that you got
over it with ease. -Yes.

00:01:10.980 --> 00:01:14.940
Can a young person handle
such great pressure?

00:01:15.700 --> 00:01:19.660
You, who achieved
significant results,

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:23.020
were expected to keep
doing the same.

00:01:23.340 --> 00:01:27.140
Is that also the reason
you got bored,

00:01:27.420 --> 00:01:31.100
and maybe you weren't
even aware of it?

00:01:31.300 --> 00:01:34.860
At one point, I acted lost.

00:01:36.557 --> 00:01:40.353
That happened when I was about
to move from the junior

00:01:40.494 --> 00:01:43.174
to the senior skiing category.

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:48.860
What happened was that I suddenly
lost around 20 to 30 kilos.

00:01:49.540 --> 00:01:51.580
And I was very thin.

00:01:51.704 --> 00:01:53.584
You only ate tangerines
and drank water?

00:01:53.674 --> 00:01:55.834
Yes, and I ate popcorn.

00:02:00.460 --> 00:02:05.980
I asked myself then, now that
I'm skiing in the senior level,

00:02:06.103 --> 00:02:08.783
what does everyone want from me?

00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:16.751
Okay, I know I'm good,
promising, healthy,

00:02:18.678 --> 00:02:21.490
but why should I now...

00:02:23.365 --> 00:02:26.820
I felt like I started doing
athletics instead of skiing.

00:02:26.949 --> 00:02:30.676
As if I had started playing
a new sport, in approach.

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:36.192
During that period,
I felt a bit lost mentally.

00:02:37.660 --> 00:02:41.180
I wasn’t sure what to do.

00:02:42.500 --> 00:02:45.180
I needed to get stronger,
and then I’d come and see

00:02:45.420 --> 00:02:47.900
other competitors looking serious.

00:02:48.961 --> 00:02:51.578
I thought they took it seriously.

00:02:52.015 --> 00:02:57.625
I didn’t know how to adapt.
At one point, I felt lost.

00:02:57.881 --> 00:03:01.594
And then after that whole
season, as it was,

00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:05.460
I felt weak and couldn’t
get any results.

00:03:06.575 --> 00:03:08.895
After that season,
I started feeling better.

00:03:09.438 --> 00:03:16.118
And I realized that what others
were saying didn’t matter.

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:22.300
For me personally. And that I had
to focus only on myself.

00:03:22.540 --> 00:03:25.180
And keep thinking
the way I did before,

00:03:25.380 --> 00:03:27.780
without letting outside
factors affect me.

00:03:27.980 --> 00:03:31.100
I thought I knew nothing
about this new field.

00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:36.060
They knew and told me
what I should do,

00:03:36.340 --> 00:03:39.140
and I didn’t feel comfortable
because of it.

00:03:39.380 --> 00:03:45.952
I didn’t want to do things
the way others said.

00:03:46.461 --> 00:03:49.389
But at that moment you were
only 17, competing against

00:03:49.528 --> 00:03:52.225
skiers who were 28 or 30,
or even older. -That's right.

00:03:52.324 --> 00:03:55.210
That’s considered the highest
achievement in any sport.

00:03:55.389 --> 00:03:58.951
After that, I acted a bit lost,
then I realized

00:03:59.110 --> 00:04:01.268
I couldn’t go on like that.

00:04:01.412 --> 00:04:05.955
And I started behaving
as I had before.

00:04:08.420 --> 00:04:15.860
You always had a "national charge."

00:04:17.580 --> 00:04:22.500
We know you didn’t like to defend
Croatia’s colors any more

00:04:22.700 --> 00:04:26.965
than me or anyone else,
but the rest of us had clubs

00:04:27.093 --> 00:04:28.813
and national teams.

00:04:29.091 --> 00:04:34.184
You didn’t have a club,
you only had a coat of arms

00:04:34.403 --> 00:04:38.620
that said Hrvatska or Croatia,
and you had an anthem.

00:04:38.860 --> 00:04:42.020
From one side, that was great,
you had motivation.

00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:45.940
But from the other side,
it was a lot of pressure.

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:48.620
Can a young person...

00:04:48.860 --> 00:04:51.100
It wasn’t easy for you,
especially when people

00:04:51.340 --> 00:04:54.140
were used to good results.

00:04:54.380 --> 00:04:57.500
At that time, Croatia was
a young country needing proof.

00:04:57.740 --> 00:05:02.325
I think that’s why it was easy
for people to like you.

00:05:02.442 --> 00:05:05.700
However, it was hard to maintain that.
That was the problem.

00:05:05.860 --> 00:05:08.780
But I maintained it
with good results.

00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:13.500
That’s exactly what I mean. But those
results had to be achieved.

00:05:13.700 --> 00:05:16.860
You have to know that I didn’t
always win downhill.

00:05:17.140 --> 00:05:23.380
I have only one downhill win.
-But you were always on top.

00:05:23.528 --> 00:05:25.648
I had a certain consistency.

00:05:25.746 --> 00:05:29.414
Nobody is 100% successful,
but you were always among the best.

00:05:29.522 --> 00:05:32.827
Every now and then you’d win
a medal, and we’d hear

00:05:32.985 --> 00:05:35.023
the Croatian national anthem.

00:05:35.272 --> 00:05:39.764
It was phenomenal how you
promoted your country.

00:05:40.622 --> 00:05:44.655
But I think it was an additional
pressure at the same time.

00:05:45.244 --> 00:05:48.537
You can only blame yourself
for that pressure, no one else.

00:05:48.624 --> 00:05:50.693
You absolutely can’t blame
anyone else for it.

00:05:50.819 --> 00:05:53.499
Not your father, not your mother,
not Croatia, nor the world.

00:05:55.358 --> 00:05:58.728
Because you are the one
who skis. It would be...

00:05:58.908 --> 00:06:03.463
I’ve never decided whether
it’s selfish of people

00:06:05.298 --> 00:06:10.158
to put pressure on you,
or selfish of you, me...

00:06:10.478 --> 00:06:15.071
Because it doesn’t matter to me
that someone else thinks

00:06:15.258 --> 00:06:17.620
I should be first.

00:06:17.797 --> 00:06:22.477
It’s because of people,
but hard to reach that level.

00:06:22.900 --> 00:06:30.484
You simply realize it doesn’t matter
what anyone thinks of you.

00:06:31.420 --> 00:06:35.020
Who cares? And why?

00:06:35.269 --> 00:06:37.930
In theory, it sounds easy,
but in practice it’s hard.

00:06:38.080 --> 00:06:40.712
I have a problem with that too.
-To understand it.

00:06:41.020 --> 00:06:43.620
To struggle with both
failures and success.

00:06:44.060 --> 00:06:49.820
Everyone has a problem with that.
But what you say is right.

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:55.140
But to achieve and maintain
not caring what others think...

00:06:55.380 --> 00:06:58.180
Who can really live like that?
Maybe Ibrahimović?

00:06:58.420 --> 00:07:01.660
Whatever others say,
he just replies he’s the best.

00:07:01.860 --> 00:07:03.700
But he’s an exception.

00:07:03.940 --> 00:07:08.900
Most people feel pressure
from duty and expectation.

00:07:09.140 --> 00:07:13.940
I know, but people also must
understand that for me

00:07:14.220 --> 00:07:17.340
it’s important to be the best.

00:07:17.780 --> 00:07:21.536
I don’t need anyone to remind me,
because I already know it.

00:07:23.067 --> 00:07:25.187
Let’s go back to skiing.

00:07:28.740 --> 00:07:33.700
For any success, not only in sports,
work is essential.

00:07:34.180 --> 00:07:39.740
But what kind of person
must one be to ski well?

00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:42.500
What potential must they have?

00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:47.220
It’s not just training that matters.
Talent matters too. -Yes, it’s important.

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:52.940
You must have a talent
for movement.

00:07:54.540 --> 00:07:58.780
Motor skills are key,
like in football. Brain to leg.

00:07:59.060 --> 00:08:03.940
If I found myself alone
in a stadium of 80,000 people,

00:08:04.180 --> 00:08:08.820
I couldn’t even pass the ball to myself.
Because I’d feel scared.

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:11.780
And the great thing about skiing
is that you feel alone.

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:17.100
You’re not even aware
of the people around you.

00:08:17.340 --> 00:08:22.224
You know they are there.
-I know, and I don't know what, but...

00:08:22.808 --> 00:08:27.648
But you're not aware of it like when
you walk into a crowded stadium.

00:08:28.100 --> 00:08:32.340
When I come to the stadium
as a fan and hear all that noise,

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:37.140
I’d just lie down on the field
and start digging with my hands.

00:08:37.380 --> 00:08:40.740
But I tell the players
to just "switch off".

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:43.780
It's hard for me to "switch off"
at the stadium, but not when I ski.

00:08:43.980 --> 00:08:46.060
Because while I'm skiing,
I'm moving fast,

00:08:46.182 --> 00:08:48.342
and they're standing still.

00:08:48.518 --> 00:08:52.698
People can tell me what they want,
but I simply reach the goal quickly.

00:08:53.180 --> 00:08:55.700
And where can you escape
from the football field?

00:08:56.140 --> 00:08:59.188
But I also run.
-Yes, but on the field.

00:08:59.337 --> 00:09:02.420
You run left or right,
you can’t run out of the stadium.

00:09:05.300 --> 00:09:11.020
All right. So motor skills are important,
and of course courage, strength, mass.

00:09:11.420 --> 00:09:15.410
But the psyche matters too.
-Yes, of course it does.

00:09:15.575 --> 00:09:17.871
Because everything
starts from the head.

00:09:18.108 --> 00:09:23.363
A man can make his muscles strong.
But muscles alone can’t do anything

00:09:24.180 --> 00:09:27.121
without commands from the brain.

00:09:28.423 --> 00:09:32.303
You can be the strongest man alive,
but if you’re not mentally ready

00:09:33.020 --> 00:09:35.460
and sure that you can lift the most,

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:39.500
no matter how easy it looks,
you just lift that weight.

00:09:40.020 --> 00:09:42.660
Explain to us how you learn
how the course looks like.

00:09:42.900 --> 00:09:47.780
It’s just routine work for me.
It’s very easy to learn.

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:52.100
People approach memorizing gates
on the course differently.

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:56.167
Some do it in detail, others don’t.
I always did it in detail.

00:09:56.315 --> 00:09:59.948
I like to prepare well. I don’t like
when something surprises me.

00:10:00.104 --> 00:10:03.956
And when something does,
I like to be ready for it.

00:10:04.104 --> 00:10:09.540
So I can instantly offer
three solutions to the problem.

00:10:09.980 --> 00:10:12.860
I know skiing, but not too much.

00:10:13.100 --> 00:10:21.700
I got even more interested
while preparing for this interview.

00:10:24.420 --> 00:10:28.820
You prepare for every race,
but things often happen

00:10:29.100 --> 00:10:33.140
that you only discover
once you reach the track.

00:10:33.460 --> 00:10:40.823
When we’d go to inspect the course,
preparing for slalom or giant slalom,

00:10:41.023 --> 00:10:46.042
the coach was allowed to visit
the course one day earlier,

00:10:46.309 --> 00:10:48.960
unless the weather didn’t allow it.

00:10:49.214 --> 00:10:53.495
So it was often done
on the day of the race.

00:10:54.366 --> 00:11:00.420
On paper, the coach draws the course
with blue and red gates. You can’t miss.

00:11:01.260 --> 00:11:07.900
He tries to describe it on paper,
and this is called a "tunnel" in skiing.

00:11:08.340 --> 00:11:15.250
The distance between blue and
red gates can be larger or smaller,

00:11:15.610 --> 00:11:18.016
which means the rhythm changes.

00:11:18.260 --> 00:11:25.291
On that paper, he tries to describe
as best as he can what awaits you.

00:11:25.446 --> 00:11:28.630
So you think about it
before going to sleep.

00:11:28.784 --> 00:11:31.188
And the next day, when you come
to inspect the course,

00:11:31.396 --> 00:11:33.396
you’ve already memorized
about 50% of it.

00:11:33.590 --> 00:11:40.999
You have visualization. -That’s right.
Then you learn the course faster.

00:11:42.060 --> 00:11:45.928
Of course, when you come to
inspect the course, it looks perfect.

00:11:46.010 --> 00:11:48.311
It’s "ironed", not a single mark on it.

00:11:48.417 --> 00:11:51.483
But if you start 40th,
it’s no longer the same track.

00:11:51.646 --> 00:11:56.561
There’ll be 40 holes,
and you have to adapt.

00:11:56.782 --> 00:11:59.542
You only realize that once you see it,
once you’re actually there.

00:11:59.642 --> 00:12:02.322
Yes, you only see it
once you’re on the course.

00:12:02.421 --> 00:12:05.311
I’m at one gate, and 10 meters
away is the next one.

00:12:05.423 --> 00:12:07.503
In those 10 meters,
in that one second,

00:12:07.642 --> 00:12:10.514
I have to decide how I’m going
to go through that gate.

00:12:10.648 --> 00:12:15.928
Is that instinct then? -If you do a lot
of repetitions, if you train a lot,

00:12:16.199 --> 00:12:20.077
and especially if you train
under those kinds of conditions,

00:12:20.268 --> 00:12:24.124
then you’ll adapt much more easily.
But if you only train on perfect slopes,

00:12:24.350 --> 00:12:28.750
you won’t have that experience,
it’s basically a new discipline to you.

00:12:28.927 --> 00:12:31.409
It’s still slalom, but it’s
a slalom with an extra element,

00:12:31.548 --> 00:12:33.788
I don’t even know what to call it.

00:12:34.341 --> 00:12:38.096
Sometimes the wind blows hard
and the terrain configuration shifts.

00:12:38.222 --> 00:12:42.675
Or the sun comes out, or there’s fog,
at those altitudes it changes in seconds.

00:12:42.870 --> 00:12:46.630
Exactly. The hardest conditions
to ski in are under diffused light.

00:12:46.785 --> 00:12:48.665
Diffused light isn’t fog,

00:12:48.817 --> 00:12:51.537
it’s when there’s a glare
from the opposite mountain,

00:12:51.714 --> 00:12:54.074
or when the sun is behind your back.

00:12:54.338 --> 00:12:58.178
You literally can’t tell whether
you’re on the ground or floating.

00:12:58.386 --> 00:13:03.163
That’s the hardest part. But yes,
that’s where the approach changes,

00:13:03.327 --> 00:13:05.874
and I’ve always been able to
compare myself with my brother:

00:13:06.028 --> 00:13:08.609
the way he did things
and the way I did them.

00:13:08.723 --> 00:13:11.043
We basically did
everything differently.

00:13:12.340 --> 00:13:15.923
It’s such a complex sport,
and that’s shown, for example,

00:13:16.053 --> 00:13:18.534
in the super combination, right?
In the morning you do a slalom...

00:13:18.639 --> 00:13:20.909
Before, it used to be a great
combination, the real deal,

00:13:21.042 --> 00:13:23.430
and then later they introduced
the super combination...

00:13:28.220 --> 00:13:30.705
I think that was done to
make the sport more accessible,

00:13:30.828 --> 00:13:33.770
to bring it closer to people
who might not be as exceptional,

00:13:33.881 --> 00:13:36.122
to make it more accessible
to a broader audience.

00:13:36.246 --> 00:13:40.627
Everyone wants to succeed and get
their opportunity, that’s how I see it.

00:13:42.620 --> 00:13:49.420
But many of these so-called
"attractiveness" adjustments,

00:13:49.780 --> 00:13:57.180
under the pretext of making it more
exciting, actually blur the line between

00:13:57.333 --> 00:14:00.373
someone who’s truly high quality
and can solve problems when they appear,

00:14:00.465 --> 00:14:02.825
and someone who’s just average.

00:14:03.214 --> 00:14:08.002
For example, take slalom, it’s
the easiest to illustrate there.

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:13.233
Slalom courses used to be
completely different.

00:14:13.418 --> 00:14:17.084
Not only were the slopes rougher,
no snow groomers or machines

00:14:17.178 --> 00:14:19.967
to smooth everything out,
it was literally like a rodeo.

00:14:20.272 --> 00:14:22.850
And they never used to set
the gates with measuring tapes.

00:14:22.951 --> 00:14:25.711
And when you’re going downhill on skis,
you can’t really judge

00:14:25.827 --> 00:14:28.482
whether something is 10 meters
away from you, or 9, or 8 meters,

00:14:28.575 --> 00:14:31.443
but that difference matters
when you have 70 gates.

00:14:31.521 --> 00:14:34.013
Now everything is done
with a measuring tape.

00:14:34.135 --> 00:14:36.693
I take a meter and
measure everything,

00:14:36.821 --> 00:14:39.670
you go up there, and if you know how to
stand on skis, you measure 10 meters,

00:14:39.810 --> 00:14:42.717
plant the pole, drill the hole,
move on another 10 meters...

00:14:42.940 --> 00:14:47.700
It requires no skill at all,
no real knowledge.

00:14:48.580 --> 00:14:54.744
And then the skier standing
at the start, skis down that course

00:14:55.380 --> 00:15:01.500
with the same rhythm from start to
finish. There’s zero skill involved.

00:15:01.740 --> 00:15:08.802
If you shift just one gate slightly off,
or shorten the distance by one meter,

00:15:09.318 --> 00:15:13.293
half of the competitors would be out
of the race. Because they don’t think.

00:15:13.410 --> 00:15:17.380
Yes, yes. -They just go
automatically, from start to finish.

00:15:17.660 --> 00:15:21.740
So, generally, I think sports,
at least some of them,

00:15:21.980 --> 00:15:25.922
of course, you can’t put them all
together in the same category,

00:15:26.032 --> 00:15:29.703
have started to function in a way
that brings the less skilled ones

00:15:29.873 --> 00:15:34.336
closer to those who are truly
exceptional. -To make it more even...

00:15:34.453 --> 00:15:37.523
They’ve lowered the standards a bit.
-Yes, yes, exactly.

00:15:37.681 --> 00:15:41.797
But if we had those truly
challenging courses again,

00:15:42.220 --> 00:15:46.300
half of the people who
suddenly appeared out of nowhere,

00:15:46.540 --> 00:15:52.236
would simply vanish on those real
tracks. -Exactly. It's clear to me.

00:15:54.300 --> 00:16:02.660
Of all those components, the mind,
motor skills, everything combined...

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:10.073
Where did you see yourself as being
better than others? What was it?

00:16:10.846 --> 00:16:14.900
Or was it the whole package?
-I don’t think I was better in anything.

00:16:15.140 --> 00:16:19.540
Then in everything? -I just made
better use of my abilities.

00:16:19.780 --> 00:16:23.300
I probably learned how to use my
capacities more efficiently.

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:27.260
And that’s what makes you better.

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:32.980
To know your body, to understand it,
to know what it can do,

00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:36.380
what your limits are,
and never go beyond them.

00:16:36.660 --> 00:16:42.740
I never went beyond my limits.
-Do you have a limit?

00:16:43.020 --> 00:16:48.140
Maybe once... When I fell, for example.
-You broke yourself, for God’s sake.

00:16:48.420 --> 00:16:51.780
When I fell during that training
session, I was still young and playful,

00:16:52.060 --> 00:16:57.077
it was fun, I had just won, and I got
carried away. I didn’t think too much,

00:16:57.620 --> 00:17:04.546
I just let myself go, and that was a
mistake. I should’ve slowed down a bit.

00:17:04.968 --> 00:17:08.366
I should’ve eased up on the tempo,
not rushed into that jump like that,

00:17:08.460 --> 00:17:10.780
because I jumped much farther
than the others.

00:17:10.941 --> 00:17:14.021
And the others, well,
that’s where experience comes in,

00:17:14.340 --> 00:17:17.700
they were more experienced
and knew that jump was tricky.

00:17:17.900 --> 00:17:22.460
I was a kid, I didn't know better...
I charged into that jump like a bull.

00:17:22.651 --> 00:17:26.942
I know, yes... -So again,
experience plays its role there.

00:17:27.553 --> 00:17:30.856
But we have to know ourselves...
I think it’s extremely important to work

00:17:30.992 --> 00:17:33.832
on both your body and your mind.

00:17:34.055 --> 00:17:39.135
You don’t have to be particularly
smart or intelligent to do that,

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:43.100
you just have to be realistic.

00:17:43.340 --> 00:17:45.660
You have to know what
you can do and what you can’t,

00:17:45.900 --> 00:17:52.317
and within what you can do,
try to get the absolute most out of it.

00:17:55.940 --> 00:18:00.860
That’s something very individual,
it’s not universal.

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:04.921
But, I don’t know, people generally
prefer to deal with other people,

00:18:05.053 --> 00:18:07.945
to analyze others, what someone else
does and how they do it,

00:18:08.053 --> 00:18:10.454
rather than deal with themselves.

00:18:10.579 --> 00:18:13.412
That’s just how I see it,
though I might be wrong.

00:18:14.380 --> 00:18:17.994
True, and you also have
that versatility of yours.

00:18:18.162 --> 00:18:21.314
You’re one of, what,
three or so female skiers

00:18:21.491 --> 00:18:26.127
who have won in all five disciplines,
right? Which one is the hardest?

00:18:26.249 --> 00:18:29.455
Can you even choose?
-The hardest is giant slalom.

00:18:29.660 --> 00:18:34.283
Harder than Super-G? -Yes.
-Why? It looks the easiest to me.

00:18:34.418 --> 00:18:38.658
Timing. I don’t know if I should
call it timing or the moment.

00:18:38.992 --> 00:18:42.152
Giant slalom is specific because

00:18:42.402 --> 00:18:49.088
the timing of entering a new turn
is absolutely crucial.

00:18:49.380 --> 00:18:55.072
There’s only one person who truly
mastered that, well, after Ted Ligety,

00:18:55.197 --> 00:18:58.049
maybe for a time, the American,
Ingemar Stenmark.

00:18:58.145 --> 00:19:01.385
Everyone knows him,
even people who don’t follow skiing.

00:19:01.950 --> 00:19:08.853
He was the man who skied
giant slalom with perfect timing.

00:19:11.232 --> 00:19:14.220
Because depending on the distance
between the gates,

00:19:14.300 --> 00:19:17.500
you basically must never
stop moving, that’s the trick,

00:19:17.780 --> 00:19:24.711
but it’s incredibly hard to achieve
that in relation to that spacing.

00:19:25.020 --> 00:19:30.868
In slalom, you automatically get
the rhythm from the course itself,

00:19:31.060 --> 00:19:33.860
but here you have to create the rhythm,
to find that precise moment

00:19:34.100 --> 00:19:37.620
when to finish one turn
and start the next.

00:19:37.743 --> 00:19:40.183
That’s really difficult and demanding.

00:19:40.314 --> 00:19:42.794
It’s a bit easier now
with modern carving skis,

00:19:42.886 --> 00:19:45.348
but before, it was much tougher.

00:19:45.549 --> 00:19:50.425
That’s why with giant slalom,
one day I’d be skiing for the win,

00:19:50.620 --> 00:19:53.820
and the next day it was as if
I’d forgotten everything.

00:19:54.006 --> 00:19:57.597
I could never find any sort of...
I don’t know... universal formula.

00:19:57.724 --> 00:19:59.834
It drove me crazy, it was so frustrating

00:19:59.934 --> 00:20:02.370
because I couldn’t figure out
a consistent solution.

00:20:02.452 --> 00:20:05.016
So it’s really about feeling, right?
-Yes, it’s all about feeling.

00:20:05.108 --> 00:20:07.771
That sense of... -Because in slalom
it’s clear... -There you have rhythm.

00:20:07.875 --> 00:20:10.037
It’s almost mathematical.
Everyone knows where they should be,

00:20:10.147 --> 00:20:12.912
it’s just about who’s faster, who’s
sharper... -Not exactly, but in slalom

00:20:13.026 --> 00:20:17.209
everything happens within a certain
dynamic, gates come one after another.

00:20:17.300 --> 00:20:19.630
In giant slalom, they don’t.

00:20:19.792 --> 00:20:22.685
You have to either
add or take away tempo,

00:20:22.879 --> 00:20:28.505
to find the right moment when to
end one turn and start the next.

00:20:29.121 --> 00:20:31.401
So for me, giant slalom was the hardest.

00:20:31.532 --> 00:20:34.892
As for Super-G and downhill...
Downhill is pure enjoyment.

00:20:35.045 --> 00:20:40.326
You’re going fast, but you have
the time and space to act.

00:20:40.620 --> 00:20:43.940
It’s difficult because of
the forces involved, of course,

00:20:44.220 --> 00:20:48.540
but overall, there’s room, it’s not like
in slalom, where you have to react

00:20:48.740 --> 00:20:53.060
in a split second or you’ll miss a gate.
In downhill, the gates are far apart,

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:57.180
and you have plenty of space
to choose your line.

00:20:57.460 --> 00:20:59.820
So, for example,
I really enjoyed downhill.

00:20:59.973 --> 00:21:02.613
Slalom was the one I liked the least,
yet it was the one I was best at.

00:21:02.745 --> 00:21:08.205
Giant slalom was fun for me, but I could
never find the right formula for it.

00:21:08.403 --> 00:21:12.163
Super-G was kind of neutral,
everything about it was fine.

00:21:12.780 --> 00:21:15.688
Is the hardest race that one
they always talk about, the downhill,

00:21:15.809 --> 00:21:19.305
the most dangerous one, the downhill
in Kitzbühel or something like that?

00:21:19.429 --> 00:21:22.349
I’ve never raced there,
and I never will.

00:21:23.332 --> 00:21:27.829
After I stopped skiing, I spent
some time with my brother’s team,

00:21:28.645 --> 00:21:31.685
and I can tell you, those men’s
downhills and what they ski...

00:21:32.860 --> 00:21:37.980
Something’s not right in their heads.
Seriously, it’s insane.

00:21:38.031 --> 00:21:40.478
Kitzbühel is actually okay
compared to some others.

00:21:40.620 --> 00:21:42.720
It’s not that going down
that slope is the problem,

00:21:42.837 --> 00:21:45.244
the problem is going down fast.
You understand? -Yeah.

00:21:45.758 --> 00:21:49.604
It’s like when you’re
driving a car on the highway,

00:21:49.756 --> 00:21:52.836
if you’re going 120 or 130 km/h,
you don’t really notice the curves.

00:21:52.999 --> 00:21:55.959
But if you’re going 230 km/h, suddenly
those curves start appearing everywhere.

00:21:56.159 --> 00:22:00.319
Yes, 100%. -That’s the best
comparison I can think of.

00:22:02.540 --> 00:22:04.620
I don’t know,
those men’s downhills...

00:22:04.860 --> 00:22:11.420
Kitzbühel is tough, yes, demanding,
but then you have Bormio in Italy,

00:22:13.460 --> 00:22:18.340
that one’s just deadly. I honestly
don’t know how those guys survive it.

00:22:18.860 --> 00:22:24.580
Or Wengen, in Switzerland,
I don’t know if you’ve seen it,

00:22:24.860 --> 00:22:30.620
there’s this jump located right between
the safety net and a rock wall.

00:22:30.860 --> 00:22:33.100
It’s about twenty meters wide,

00:22:33.260 --> 00:22:36.180
and you have to jump between
the wall and the net,

00:22:36.420 --> 00:22:41.580
you can’t even see where you’re landing
and then, as soon as you hit the ground,

00:22:41.780 --> 00:22:45.660
there’s a 90 degree turn.
I swear, if it were me, I’d get there,

00:22:45.900 --> 00:22:50.100
sit down, and cry. I don’t see
any way to make it through.

00:22:50.300 --> 00:22:52.740
I watch them and think...

00:22:52.980 --> 00:22:58.060
On one side, you’ve got the safety net,
so you can either get caught in it...

00:22:58.260 --> 00:23:00.860
And that’s your ligaments gone...
-And end up dangling like a flag

00:23:01.140 --> 00:23:04.580
or you fall down one ravine,
or you get thrown off into another,

00:23:04.789 --> 00:23:09.424
because after that point
there’s literally no course left.

00:23:09.977 --> 00:23:15.346
It’s surreal to me,
that whole little "mouse hole".

00:23:15.705 --> 00:23:20.189
Every time I went there, I’d say,
"Okay, I can ski the whole thing,

00:23:20.533 --> 00:23:26.860
but here I’ll just take off my skis,
walk around, and then continue."

00:23:27.740 --> 00:23:31.300
But, well, those are men’s downhills -
they’re on another level.

00:23:31.493 --> 00:23:34.733
You’re known as someone who doesn’t hold
back. Anja Pärson said about you,

00:23:34.957 --> 00:23:39.797
about your style, that when you have
a one-second lead after the first run,

00:23:40.060 --> 00:23:45.940
in the second you still go all out.
No calculation. -Well, yes.

00:23:46.180 --> 00:23:49.549
But do you realize... -Because
the others are good. -Sure, sure...

00:23:49.726 --> 00:23:52.877
I mean, she’s good enough to make up
for that, sorry... -Right, but wait,

00:23:53.027 --> 00:23:58.630
in the second run... let’s say you have
a one-second lead after the first run.

00:23:58.827 --> 00:24:01.630
Halfway through the run,
which lasts a minute.

00:24:01.823 --> 00:24:05.458
Halfway through the run,
do you know... -No.

00:24:05.739 --> 00:24:10.192
No. Do you know that you're good,
that you're first, and probably

00:24:10.402 --> 00:24:16.130
at least a second ahead? -You don’t think
that way, about by how much you’ll win.

00:24:16.620 --> 00:24:22.860
You just think about finishing...
Actually, my goal when I skied,

00:24:23.100 --> 00:24:27.540
no matter how good I was, when I kept
winning slaloms all the time.

00:24:28.020 --> 00:24:32.787
When someone asked what my goal was.
My goal was to make the second run.

00:24:34.220 --> 00:24:39.700
It happened once.
I was great, OK.

00:24:39.980 --> 00:24:44.220
I was injured, but when
you're good and at your peak,

00:24:44.420 --> 00:24:51.620
you come back, and it never crossed
your mind you wouldn’t qualify.

00:24:52.340 --> 00:24:55.580
Knowing your quality
and all the work you’ve done.

00:24:55.820 --> 00:24:58.660
It happened to me.
That was such a slap,

00:24:58.860 --> 00:25:05.540
that I realized it’s pointless winning
if I can’t prove I’m good.

00:25:05.780 --> 00:25:10.820
When I came there, I think I was
34th or something, maybe I’m wrong,

00:25:11.500 --> 00:25:17.740
then I thought, OK, from now on,
just make the second run.

00:25:18.100 --> 00:25:24.340
Then I’ll fix it in the second run
if needed. -OK, first run’s over.

00:25:24.580 --> 00:25:30.980
And you’re first. One second ahead.
Now you start last among those

00:25:31.580 --> 00:25:40.656
who can threaten you. You start,
you know what they’re like, you know all.

00:25:41.087 --> 00:25:46.117
You ski, and halfway down,
do you know you still have that lead,

00:25:46.367 --> 00:25:50.140
because you’re skiing well... -You know...
-Then why not slow down a bit?

00:25:50.380 --> 00:25:54.460
You know how much you risk. Because
a mistake can happen anytime.

00:25:54.598 --> 00:25:58.398
And if you slow down, and then err,
you’re done. -If you push harder...

00:25:58.559 --> 00:26:01.943
You must never lower your guard.
Never drop your guard.

00:26:02.140 --> 00:26:07.180
You’re not skiing 100%,
but enough to keep your pace.

00:26:07.420 --> 00:26:11.896
You can never predict a mistake,
if it will happen or not.

00:26:11.998 --> 00:26:16.300
But if you drop your guard too much...
-I’m not talking about the guard,

00:26:16.510 --> 00:26:19.458
I mean slowing down a little
so you don’t err. -No.

00:26:19.573 --> 00:26:23.076
You control it. -But you already
control that before.

00:26:23.406 --> 00:26:26.943
You always control it.
-I always control it.

00:26:27.240 --> 00:26:32.680
For me, the key in skiing
was to make fewer mistakes.

00:26:32.860 --> 00:26:35.140
They take away a lot of time.

00:26:36.475 --> 00:26:39.735
That’s what I meant by efficiency.

00:26:45.573 --> 00:26:52.724
You must always be ready
to make a mistake.

00:26:52.959 --> 00:26:57.839
That you’ll need extra strength
and drive to fix it.

00:26:58.460 --> 00:27:04.180
If you go like crazy until then
and waste all your energy,

00:27:04.500 --> 00:27:09.380
you’ll have none left to correct
what you’ve done wrong.

00:27:10.540 --> 00:27:15.740
My goal in skiing was to make
as few mistakes as possible.

00:27:19.380 --> 00:27:25.380
Why let myself err
if I can be good enough,

00:27:25.940 --> 00:27:31.809
say with 80% effort,
and keep 20% for a crisis.

00:27:33.380 --> 00:27:38.660
Something like that. But you can do that
in individual sports, not sure in team ones.

00:27:38.900 --> 00:27:42.420
In a team you can even more.
-You must still know yourself well.

00:27:42.620 --> 00:27:46.060
You must know your abilities.
What you’re ready to do on which course,

00:27:46.300 --> 00:27:50.020
or what’s possible. You must know
which course you like,

00:27:50.220 --> 00:27:56.140
how it’s set up,
what doesn’t suit you best.

00:27:56.436 --> 00:28:08.375
You must know what to do on which
part to minimize your weaknesses.

00:28:10.864 --> 00:28:15.904
When you mentioned
course setting a few times.

00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:19.600
What does that actually
mean in practice?

00:28:19.889 --> 00:28:24.691
Your father was often called out by
Austrians, Swiss... -He set courses

00:28:24.893 --> 00:28:28.093
where you had to think.
-That suited you.

00:28:28.420 --> 00:28:31.700
What does that mean in practice?
Is there someone who approves it,

00:28:31.940 --> 00:28:35.580
or can you set it as you wish?
There are rules you must follow.

00:28:35.820 --> 00:28:39.340
You can place one gate here,
and another further down. -Yeah.

00:28:39.700 --> 00:28:48.500
There are FIS rules for that.
Of course, they change over the years.

00:28:48.700 --> 00:28:54.300
One year it was popular
to set slalom gates 15 meters apart.

00:28:54.500 --> 00:28:58.660
That’s almost like giant slalom.

00:28:59.340 --> 00:29:04.660
On the course you can place gates
from 8 to 15 meters apart.

00:29:04.860 --> 00:29:10.860
Of course, if you place one gate
at 8, another at 15, then 8 again,

00:29:11.100 --> 00:29:16.100
you break their rhythm. -Exactly.
-Not everyone can adapt to that.

00:29:16.263 --> 00:29:19.153
Then it's easiest for people
to say that it's complicated.

00:29:19.300 --> 00:29:23.420
Of course it's complicated,
make an effort. Think.

00:29:23.780 --> 00:29:29.740
I never understood how my dad
was setting the course wrong.

00:29:30.110 --> 00:29:33.030
He was doing exactly what
we do in training.

00:29:33.207 --> 00:29:39.547
He made it fun. It's not like you just
put in a tape and it plays on repeat.

00:29:39.678 --> 00:29:42.765
Like chicks that all
come out of the incubator.

00:29:44.555 --> 00:29:49.414
That's terrible. -That gives
you room to be creative.

00:29:50.780 --> 00:29:54.900
When everything’s the same,
creativity means nothing.

00:29:56.020 --> 00:30:02.060
Because everything’s the same. -Basically
it’s like that... Like in super combined,

00:30:02.300 --> 00:30:06.260
when you ski slalom at 10 a.m.
with one pair of skis, boots tied that way,

00:30:06.500 --> 00:30:11.900
and at 1 p.m. it’s downhill where
skis are half a meter longer...

00:30:12.300 --> 00:30:15.980
That’s a funny transition.
-How do you switch to that?

00:30:16.180 --> 00:30:18.980
Downhill is usually run first.
The exception was at the Olympics

00:30:19.220 --> 00:30:23.300
in Salt Lake City. Because of the weather,
slalom was first, then downhill.

00:30:23.540 --> 00:30:27.580
That was actually a good thing
for me, how it turned out.

00:30:27.780 --> 00:30:29.900
It really was...

00:30:31.500 --> 00:30:37.020
A funny thing is when from 212 cm
skis you have to go to 150 cm ones,

00:30:38.220 --> 00:30:44.860
that are 20 kilos lighter.
It’s literally like you wear nothing.

00:30:45.540 --> 00:30:51.460
You’ve got slow legs because your fibers
are slow. In downhill nothing happens fast.

00:30:52.860 --> 00:30:58.060
A different muscle group works.
In slalom, it’s the fast fibers.

00:30:59.100 --> 00:31:04.260
In downhill you must be more refined.
You need a really good feeling.

00:31:04.500 --> 00:31:08.420
In downhill, feeling is crucial,
in slalom you don’t need any.

00:31:08.541 --> 00:31:12.141
You just hit as hard as you can.

00:31:13.660 --> 00:31:19.540
What’s the role... No, how big is
the role of people we don’t see?

00:31:19.740 --> 00:31:25.420
The team in the shadows. Technicians.
We know in Formula 1 you see them,

00:31:25.620 --> 00:31:31.020
they prepare tires, the whole race,
right? The people in the pit stop.

00:31:31.246 --> 00:31:36.646
And in skiing, ski size, wax,
length of poles and so on.

00:31:36.980 --> 00:31:40.740
How much difference does that make?
Do you take part in it?

00:31:40.940 --> 00:31:45.700
My technician was a magician.
I was lucky we came across

00:31:45.900 --> 00:31:51.860
Jure Hafner. Before that I had some
other technicians, at first it was dad.

00:31:52.100 --> 00:31:55.100
When we were kids, he did it.
When things got more serious,

00:31:55.340 --> 00:32:00.540
you could get a technician
from the ski manufacturer.

00:32:01.100 --> 00:32:06.220
When it comes to skis, he’s key.
Like everyone, you know that.

00:32:06.420 --> 00:32:09.220
Every team member
has their own task,

00:32:09.460 --> 00:32:16.380
which is no less important than,
say, what my dad does.

00:32:16.620 --> 00:32:22.803
He’s not the head coach, of course,
but the physio, and especially the tech.

00:32:22.950 --> 00:32:26.881
Huge, huge importance.
Very important. Enormous.

00:32:27.045 --> 00:32:32.475
Even the person... I remember
in America it was -50.

00:32:32.690 --> 00:32:36.107
You have to undress to your suit,
and ski down.

00:32:36.310 --> 00:32:40.420
Even the person who just carries
your jacket - when I get down,

00:32:40.620 --> 00:32:43.380
so I can get dressed.
It seems trivial, but it matters.

00:32:43.620 --> 00:32:48.460
I’d reach the bottom half-naked
and have to ride the lift at -50.

00:32:49.300 --> 00:32:56.900
Not exactly wow things,
but they matter in the end for success.

00:32:57.620 --> 00:33:02.700
Without each of those little puzzle
pieces, there’d be nothing.

00:33:02.900 --> 00:33:07.540
No one’s irreplaceable,
but we had a steady team

00:33:07.900 --> 00:33:13.540
that worked really well.
In Croatia there aren’t many skiers.

00:33:13.740 --> 00:33:17.700
We raced with Slovenians
and in their competitions.

00:33:17.940 --> 00:33:25.823
When I was a kid, since
organized skiing in Croatia existed,

00:33:26.315 --> 00:33:31.175
but there wasn’t much competition,
we were in the Slovenian region.

00:33:32.180 --> 00:33:38.981
We competed with them.
It was great that they allowed us

00:33:40.340 --> 00:33:45.820
to ski in their national
championship. -Yes.

00:33:51.180 --> 00:33:56.220
Skiing is your sport.
Do you like other sports?

00:33:56.460 --> 00:34:04.020
Which ones? -I like watching football,
because it relaxes me.

00:34:05.140 --> 00:34:10.788
Why does it relax you?
It’s boring? -No, it’s not...

00:34:14.020 --> 00:34:24.168
It has a flow that’s not too demanding,
but it keeps you engaged.

00:34:24.965 --> 00:34:29.340
And still, if at one moment...
If the match lasts long, it’s fine.

00:34:29.493 --> 00:34:32.453
If you look away for a moment,
you probably won’t miss much.

00:34:32.685 --> 00:34:38.997
-100%. -You probably won’t turn
when the commentator yells

00:34:39.193 --> 00:34:45.100
that someone’s close to scoring.
And that passing...

00:34:45.380 --> 00:34:48.660
Maybe because I’m really bad
at football.

00:34:48.900 --> 00:34:52.260
Handball I’m good at, with hands fine.
But football never...

00:34:52.460 --> 00:34:57.290
It’d make more sense that link
head-feet works. -But no.

00:34:57.620 --> 00:35:04.110
Two left feet. I just never
managed football.

00:35:04.407 --> 00:35:09.505
Probably because I never could,
it fascinated me more. -Yes, yes.

00:35:09.700 --> 00:35:13.500
What all you can do with it.
Those free kicks,

00:35:13.740 --> 00:35:17.020
when the ball flies everywhere.
For me it’s like... how?

00:35:17.260 --> 00:35:24.063
You kick the ball, it goes straight.
But it doesn’t, it bends and swerves.

00:35:24.222 --> 00:35:28.626
And those precise passes. I don’t know,
Beckham, or Roberto Carlos.

00:35:28.924 --> 00:35:31.044
That’s strange to me too.

00:35:33.700 --> 00:35:39.020
It fascinates me how someone
can use the foot like a hand.

00:35:39.260 --> 00:35:43.060
A hand’s a hand, you have control,
but with the foot you don’t have

00:35:43.300 --> 00:35:46.780
that fine motor control.
Nor do you train it.

00:35:47.020 --> 00:35:51.172
As a child, everything you do,
you do with your hands.

00:35:51.265 --> 00:35:53.656
You develop fine motor skills
with your hands.

00:35:53.814 --> 00:36:00.797
What would you do with your feet?
Play piano? Or draw with them?

00:36:01.513 --> 00:36:05.969
You don’t develop that fine control.
You just walk and run.

00:36:06.440 --> 00:36:11.200
Then you have to start. That’s what
interests me about football.

00:36:12.140 --> 00:36:16.060
﻿I kind of love all sports in general...
I even love watching figure skating.

00:36:16.260 --> 00:36:18.500
Does that relax you? -Yes.

00:36:18.740 --> 00:36:23.220
And gymnastics. I think it’s amazing.
And I absolutely love hockey.

00:36:23.500 --> 00:36:26.544
See, I can’t watch hockey,
’cause my eyesight’s not that good.

00:36:26.639 --> 00:36:29.028
I only realize it’s a goal
when they start celebrating.

00:36:29.168 --> 00:36:31.463
Yeah. -I can’t see the puck.
You can’t see the puck either.

00:36:31.624 --> 00:36:33.984
Come on, don’t tell me
you can actually see that puck!

00:36:34.118 --> 00:36:37.190
Of course you can see the puck!
-When you’re watching live?

00:36:37.428 --> 00:36:40.533
Well, that’s the thing... yeah.
The speed of the game, the decisions,

00:36:40.896 --> 00:36:44.682
the movement, the coordination,
it’s all so tough.

00:36:44.857 --> 00:36:47.839
It’s the connection between your eyes
and the space around you.

00:36:47.960 --> 00:36:51.151
And it’s super aerobic.
-You’re using both your legs and arms...

00:36:51.220 --> 00:36:54.940
It’s really hard to make all that work
so fast in such a small area.

00:36:55.180 --> 00:36:59.740
It’s demanding.
-And with your heart rate at 200!

00:36:59.940 --> 00:37:01.940
So tell me this...

00:37:02.900 --> 00:37:10.460
A lot of athletes, especially champions
from individual sports,

00:37:11.260 --> 00:37:14.700
say they’d struggle to adapt
to being part of a team.

00:37:14.940 --> 00:37:17.940
They don’t like depending on others.

00:37:18.180 --> 00:37:23.340
Earlier you mentioned
the handball goalkeeper, even the coach.

00:37:23.820 --> 00:37:28.940
Do you think you could be
part of a team?

00:37:29.940 --> 00:37:33.020
That’s a tough question.
I don’t think so.

00:37:33.220 --> 00:37:37.020
Why not? -Not because of the team itself,
but because of the referee.

00:37:37.152 --> 00:37:39.305
Wherever there’s a referee,
there’s injustice.

00:37:39.414 --> 00:37:42.054
And referees are everywhere,
except in skiing.

00:37:42.295 --> 00:37:46.415
For example, I’ll never understand
you football players.

00:37:46.546 --> 00:37:51.866
When you start diving, wasting time...
There should be someone on the sidelines

00:37:52.061 --> 00:37:56.532
who runs in, picks you up, and says,
"Come on, get on with it!"

00:37:56.768 --> 00:38:02.462
Because honestly, it’s none of
my business, but I just don’t get it,

00:38:02.599 --> 00:38:05.712
what do you gain from
wasting someone else’s time?

00:38:05.868 --> 00:38:09.790
Because next time, someone’s gonna
waste yours, and you’ll be mad at him.

00:38:09.902 --> 00:38:13.149
It’s that simple rule: "Don’t do to others
what you wouldn’t want done to you."

00:38:13.308 --> 00:38:17.849
Alright, don’t take it that far.
-No, that’s just how it is. Period.

00:38:17.992 --> 00:38:21.512
There’s no reason to steal someone’s time.
Who do you think you are,

00:38:21.626 --> 00:38:26.660
to take away something
that belongs to someone else,

00:38:27.581 --> 00:38:32.668
like the time left
until the end of the match?

00:38:34.434 --> 00:38:37.871
You want to win, and sure,
that’s a bit Machiavellian.

00:38:38.147 --> 00:38:41.467
The end justifies the means.
-Yeah, but you should win fairly.

00:38:41.653 --> 00:38:45.543
A win that isn’t honest and fair
isn’t worth a dime.

00:38:45.820 --> 00:38:53.672
I totally agree, in general, but it depends
on the situation, the context.

00:38:53.904 --> 00:38:58.672
What you’re saying
is almost Nobel Prize-worthy.

00:39:02.220 --> 00:39:06.100
But I think you just have
a special relationship with time.

00:39:06.238 --> 00:39:11.456
Yeah. -You don’t really have opponents.
You’re always fighting against time itself.

00:39:11.620 --> 00:39:14.380
That’s why you respect it so much.

00:39:14.740 --> 00:39:18.260
Still, I think you’d be great
in a team sport.

00:39:18.500 --> 00:39:24.356
I’m 100% sure of it. You’re a champion,
you’ve got all the leadership qualities,

00:39:25.123 --> 00:39:28.363
but you’re also empathetic,
open, grounded.

00:39:28.875 --> 00:39:32.195
I can work well with a team,
but some of those things...

00:39:32.459 --> 00:39:36.419
You’d be captain, no doubt about it.
-...just don’t sit right with me.

00:39:36.597 --> 00:39:39.041
They don’t sit well with me either.

00:39:39.501 --> 00:39:43.557
I couldn’t handle it if something unfair
happened, not to me, and not to anyone else.

00:39:43.720 --> 00:39:46.600
Like, say we’re playing handball,
and one girl hits another,

00:39:46.723 --> 00:39:49.048
and the referee doesn’t call a foul.

00:39:49.176 --> 00:39:53.759
I’d always be the one demanding justice,
and you’re not supposed to do that.

00:39:54.205 --> 00:39:57.736
As my friend says:
"Where does the reckoning begin?"

00:39:57.820 --> 00:40:00.083
Where does injustice actually start?

00:40:00.219 --> 00:40:02.825
I could explain injustice to you,
or someone even wiser could.

00:40:02.976 --> 00:40:06.388
You can find a hundred examples
of unfairness even in skiing.

00:40:06.547 --> 00:40:09.067
You could say it’s unfair
the way a course is set up,

00:40:09.189 --> 00:40:11.865
because it might suit you better
if the spacing in slalom

00:40:12.001 --> 00:40:15.005
isn’t always the same,
if it’s not in rhythm. -I get that.

00:40:15.145 --> 00:40:18.147
Yeah, there are a hundred
little things like that.

00:40:18.323 --> 00:40:23.147
People simply want to win.
-But that’s not intentional unfairness.

00:40:23.259 --> 00:40:26.210
So why do they waste time?
To break the other player’s rhythm,

00:40:26.326 --> 00:40:29.085
to get a short rest, so the opponent
can’t score, so they can win.

00:40:29.173 --> 00:40:32.155
Is that fair, is that honest?
-It’s cheap.

00:40:32.393 --> 00:40:35.545
Maybe it’s not fair,
but it’s not rotten, either.

00:40:35.683 --> 00:40:39.905
It’s not exactly sportsmanlike.
-I don’t think so. -But what is, really?

00:40:40.108 --> 00:40:43.624
That’s why I think I wouldn’t cope well
in those kinds of situations.

00:40:43.739 --> 00:40:48.091
As part of a team, sure,
I could fit in, no problem.

00:40:48.285 --> 00:40:52.147
Skiing is an individual sport,
but you still have a team behind you.

00:40:52.294 --> 00:40:57.272
Anči, Nika Fleiss and I used to ski together
under coach Jelušić, we were a team.

00:40:57.525 --> 00:41:04.125
Even though we didn’t win medals as a team.
-Of course. But you were a team. Exactly.

00:41:04.460 --> 00:41:08.340
And it’s normal
to help each other out.

00:41:08.820 --> 00:41:14.540
You share information when you
reach the finish, what the course is like,

00:41:14.820 --> 00:41:19.020
to make it easier for the others,
so they can adjust mentally.

00:41:19.260 --> 00:41:23.180
Like: "Hey, there’s a rut there now,
I’ll need to change my line," and so on.

00:41:24.020 --> 00:41:27.860
I’ve asked everyone this,
so I’ll ask you too:

00:41:28.580 --> 00:41:31.100
Work and talent...
Without work there’s no...

00:41:31.247 --> 00:41:34.320
What? -What’s the right balance?
It doesn’t have to be in percentages,

00:41:34.460 --> 00:41:37.620
but without work,
there’s nothing, that’s clear.

00:41:37.807 --> 00:41:42.847
Still, I think there’s too much
talk about that…

00:41:43.220 --> 00:41:45.873
And you said a moment ago,
when we were talking about skiing today,

00:41:46.025 --> 00:41:49.100
that everyone’s given a chance,
that according to public opinion,

00:41:49.211 --> 00:41:52.264
anyone can do anything.
"The sky’s the limit."

00:41:52.335 --> 00:41:54.420
Everyone can do everything,
but in my opinion...

00:41:54.535 --> 00:41:57.576
Americanization? -Exactly.
But I don’t think it really works that way.

00:41:57.681 --> 00:41:59.683
Not everyone can do everything.
-No, they can’t.

00:41:59.797 --> 00:42:01.472
Everyone can do something, for sure.

00:42:01.558 --> 00:42:04.112
But not everyone’s meant for everything,
and not everything is meant for everyone.

00:42:04.221 --> 00:42:05.088
Right.

00:42:05.228 --> 00:42:10.764
The hard part is recognizing that,
realizing you’re not made for something.

00:42:10.972 --> 00:42:13.014
That’s a real blow.

00:42:13.959 --> 00:42:18.021
It’s hard to accept that you’re simply
not capable of doing something.

00:42:18.164 --> 00:42:20.324
It’s easy for me to say that now,
from this perspective,

00:42:20.493 --> 00:42:23.573
because I was capable of doing it.
You know what I mean? -I do.

00:42:23.726 --> 00:42:27.206
Some people just don’t have the capacity,
even if they try their hardest,

00:42:27.397 --> 00:42:31.197
they just don’t. -But when we’re
talking about kids and parents,

00:42:31.390 --> 00:42:35.062
there should be someone there
who can gently say,

00:42:35.145 --> 00:42:37.288
"Maybe this isn’t for you,
but maybe something else is."

00:42:37.440 --> 00:42:39.680
Because it’s a shame...

00:42:39.877 --> 00:42:43.945
It’s not that I don’t want them
to be part of sports, it’s for their sake.

00:42:44.118 --> 00:42:49.672
There are so many crushed dreams,
so much disappointment, even broken lives.

00:42:49.818 --> 00:42:52.618
Because everything was pushed
in that one direction,

00:42:52.781 --> 00:42:59.381
when that person might have succeeded
in another sport, or even another career.

00:42:59.557 --> 00:43:03.351
Yeah, I get that. And you’ve wasted years
on something that, in the end,

00:43:03.521 --> 00:43:07.180
didn’t bring any results, time you could
have spent on something else entirely.

00:43:13.149 --> 00:43:16.258
I think you can be
as talented as you want,

00:43:16.448 --> 00:43:19.248
but if you don’t work properly,
then that talent...

00:43:19.456 --> 00:43:24.816
Absolutely, but the opposite is true too.
You can be the best version of yourself

00:43:24.876 --> 00:43:28.156
through hard work, but will
you become Janica Kostelić?

00:43:28.312 --> 00:43:31.472
Well, you’ve got to have
some luck too. -Luck, yeah.

00:43:31.562 --> 00:43:34.640
Luck is a by-product
of well-organized effort.

00:43:34.752 --> 00:43:36.592
Perfect. -There you go.

00:43:38.100 --> 00:43:43.860
Tell me, how satisfied are you
with today’s sports in general?

00:43:44.820 --> 00:43:48.580
Has it drifted away from its essence,
from what it really used to be?

00:43:49.300 --> 00:43:54.300
Has it gone too far...?
-That’s a tough one to answer.

00:43:54.980 --> 00:43:57.260
You can make arguments
both for and against,

00:43:57.700 --> 00:44:02.860
so I couldn’t give a clear,
specific opinion.

00:44:03.180 --> 00:44:07.420
Things change, and that’s normal.
It’s like if, back when I was skiing actively,

00:44:07.660 --> 00:44:11.140
we had sat down and talked about
what skiing was like 50 years earlier.

00:44:11.380 --> 00:44:16.420
Things evolve and sport
has to evolve along with them.

00:44:16.620 --> 00:44:21.249
Doping? -Disgusting. -Disgusting, really?
-Yeah, I just don’t get it.

00:44:22.060 --> 00:44:26.540
Top-level sport... -It’s very common,
especially in individual disciplines.

00:44:26.670 --> 00:44:29.143
Yeah, but not really in skiing.
-No, not much in skiing.

00:44:29.250 --> 00:44:31.533
At least, I’ve never heard of it.

00:44:32.050 --> 00:44:35.756
But in elite sport we have to
understand that there’s

00:44:35.878 --> 00:44:39.303
a big difference between recreational
and professional sport.

00:44:39.500 --> 00:44:47.060
Professional sport is honestly
one of the unhealthiest things

00:44:47.620 --> 00:44:52.660
you can do to your body,
because you’re constantly pushing it

00:44:52.900 --> 00:44:57.620
to limits that aren’t natural.

00:44:59.140 --> 00:45:03.300
So even that basic realization
that you’re doing something

00:45:03.540 --> 00:45:07.146
where you’re intentionally hurting yourself
just to compete at the top level,

00:45:07.273 --> 00:45:09.673
that already says enough.

00:45:09.852 --> 00:45:14.149
You’re exhausting yourself every single day,
and then on top of that,

00:45:14.323 --> 00:45:20.516
you put substances into your body
to destroy yourself even more.

00:45:20.739 --> 00:45:26.539
How is that even possible?
I just don’t understand it.

00:45:27.100 --> 00:45:28.668
Just to run faster?

00:45:28.777 --> 00:45:31.543
That’s exactly where this idea fits in:
not everyone’s made for everything.

00:45:31.654 --> 00:45:33.754
If you can’t accept that you’re
not meant for something,

00:45:33.889 --> 00:45:35.809
then you reach for doping.

00:45:35.918 --> 00:45:39.371
But what does that medal mean to you then?
If you have to live your whole life

00:45:39.485 --> 00:45:46.085
knowing you didn’t achieve it
with your own potential?

00:45:46.223 --> 00:45:48.743
Well, you did, but something
helped you get there.

00:45:48.913 --> 00:45:51.873
You could try to justify it that way,
a bit of reverse psychology.

00:45:51.985 --> 00:45:56.305
But to me, it makes no real sense.
You’re just damaging yourself even more.

00:45:56.562 --> 00:46:00.629
If you’ve chosen to dedicate your life
to professional sport,

00:46:00.799 --> 00:46:04.119
something that’s already hard,
both mentally and physically,

00:46:04.288 --> 00:46:07.848
and then you go and take
these artificial substances

00:46:08.220 --> 00:46:12.800
to wreck yourself even further,
there’s just no need for that.

00:46:13.732 --> 00:46:17.452
You said earlier that times change
and that it’s not useful

00:46:17.698 --> 00:46:23.938
to compare eras, but you once made
a really interesting statement

00:46:24.460 --> 00:46:27.540
that I’d like you to explain.

00:46:30.573 --> 00:46:34.060
You said you’re not sure
you could achieve today

00:46:34.201 --> 00:46:37.597
what you achieved back then.
-Yes, I did say that. -And?

00:46:37.825 --> 00:46:46.183
Yeah... my character, my personality,
they’re not modern.

00:46:48.460 --> 00:46:54.020
I’m not sure people will get what I mean,
but I’m kind of old school.

00:46:57.357 --> 00:46:59.397
You mean off the slopes?

00:46:59.593 --> 00:47:04.357
No, I mean especially when it comes
to the pressure of social media.

00:47:04.548 --> 00:47:06.873
So yeah, off the slopes
you wouldn’t do so well.

00:47:06.981 --> 00:47:09.396
Back then, you had TV,
you had newspapers,

00:47:09.521 --> 00:47:11.264
and you had expectations.

00:47:11.454 --> 00:47:22.317
Nowadays, everyone online feels
entitled to form an opinion about you.

00:47:23.860 --> 00:47:29.004
And for someone young,
just starting out,

00:47:30.644 --> 00:47:32.832
someone who’s still
trying to find their footing,

00:47:32.964 --> 00:47:35.356
like I was at the beginning,
that can be really destructive.

00:47:35.519 --> 00:47:37.694
It’s dangerous, honestly.

00:47:38.416 --> 00:47:42.136
Because suddenly,
someone sitting on their couch

00:47:42.580 --> 00:47:46.020
is telling you how much you’re worth.
-And you know it’s happening.

00:47:46.220 --> 00:47:50.460
Sure, you might know your own value,
you might know who you are,

00:47:50.700 --> 00:47:53.860
but it’s hard to stay grounded
in the middle of all that noise.

00:47:54.100 --> 00:47:58.620
And you know what that person thinks,
because they’ve left a comment.

00:47:58.980 --> 00:48:04.460
I think it’s all incredibly hard to deal with.
I don’t even have Instagram,

00:48:04.660 --> 00:48:11.442
or Facebook, or any of that.
It’s fun to check in on

00:48:11.695 --> 00:48:15.695
a few friends sometimes,
but following all those

00:48:16.420 --> 00:48:21.980
"important" people on social media...
well, now everyone’s suddenly important.

00:48:22.180 --> 00:48:27.820
You are active in working with children.
You are the mother of two sons.

00:48:28.260 --> 00:48:33.620
What do you recommend to parents
and children when choosing a sport?

00:48:33.820 --> 00:48:39.002
I assume that sports are good, right?
-I’m not an expert.

00:48:40.400 --> 00:48:45.180
Will you direct your sons towards
sports? -I have a son and a daughter.

00:48:45.420 --> 00:48:49.981
A son and a daughter, yes.
-Of course, I direct them towards sports.

00:48:51.420 --> 00:48:56.708
But it’s not sports, they play there.
They go play football.

00:48:56.895 --> 00:49:01.660
For them, all of this must be
in the form of entertainment.

00:49:02.020 --> 00:49:05.701
I think that sports have
become too serious too soon.

00:49:05.858 --> 00:49:07.615
I watch my nephews...

00:49:08.946 --> 00:49:11.706
They have chosen football.

00:49:11.954 --> 00:49:16.045
That's great, but I don’t know
why boys opt for football.

00:49:16.248 --> 00:49:18.608
It is very difficult to succeed in it.

00:49:18.739 --> 00:49:21.699
Out of ten of them,
nine of them play football.

00:49:22.281 --> 00:49:27.041
There’s huge competition and
a lot of money in the game.

00:49:27.460 --> 00:49:31.041
It goes together. But I guess
you choose it because you love it.

00:49:33.268 --> 00:49:42.020
I think that serious sports take away
a part of children’s childhood.

00:49:42.620 --> 00:49:44.700
One hundred percent correct.

00:49:45.420 --> 00:49:56.620
Because a seven or eight-year-old
doesn’t need to spend so much time

00:49:56.860 --> 00:50:00.860
in a serious system of some
kind of game,

00:50:01.140 --> 00:50:07.300
because he’s not mature enough for that.
That should be more optional.

00:50:07.500 --> 00:50:12.140
Games? -Playing that league
at 7 or 8 years old, those goals...

00:50:12.340 --> 00:50:16.900
Parents pay 200 euros to score a goal?
-Everything is paid for.

00:50:17.010 --> 00:50:19.780
Ultimately, it’s not the children’s
fault, it’s the parents’ fault.

00:50:19.948 --> 00:50:22.428
Children don’t raise themselves.
Parents raise their children.

00:50:22.558 --> 00:50:24.318
We raise them.

00:50:24.532 --> 00:50:29.478
It’s not even the parents’ fault,
because if the system is so complex,

00:50:29.624 --> 00:50:33.455
that children start at six years old,
your child can’t train at nine.

00:50:34.136 --> 00:50:35.838
Maybe he can at 12?

00:50:36.135 --> 00:50:41.460
My daughter Sofi trains taekwondo.
She’s 10 years old. She just started.

00:50:41.528 --> 00:50:43.168
She trains five times a week.

00:50:43.275 --> 00:50:45.302
Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday,
Thursday, Friday.

00:50:45.421 --> 00:50:48.101
At the best taekwondo club
in the country.

00:50:48.193 --> 00:50:53.903
The club won a lot of medals.
It’s fantastic! I’m happy about it.

00:50:54.086 --> 00:50:57.646
I’m proud that she trains.
But do you have to train every day?

00:50:57.761 --> 00:51:03.388
Then I find out that some of her peers
train twice a day.

00:51:03.686 --> 00:51:08.486
I’m not for that. -We didn’t train
that much. -We didn’t.

00:51:08.768 --> 00:51:11.349
Yes, those were still romantic times.

00:51:11.463 --> 00:51:14.091
That’s one of the reasons why
I think it’s wrong.

00:51:14.229 --> 00:51:17.192
There’s too much pressure on these kids.
Just like with these mobile phones.

00:51:17.457 --> 00:51:22.138
Parents give smartphones
to their kids.

00:51:22.824 --> 00:51:26.584
They expect a seven-year-old
to know how to use

00:51:26.706 --> 00:51:31.746
the phone properly and sensibly.

00:51:32.032 --> 00:51:36.752
They’ve given kids a responsibility
that they can’t handle.

00:51:36.859 --> 00:51:39.473
And then the children are to blame?
How are they to blame?

00:51:39.592 --> 00:51:44.379
So don’t give him a smartphone.
Give them a regular one, just to call.

00:51:46.020 --> 00:51:49.220
There’s too much responsibility on kids.
-That’s true.

00:51:49.580 --> 00:51:54.620
There’s too much responsibility.
They have to be emotionally mature.

00:51:54.860 --> 00:51:57.220
They have to do this,
they have to do that.

00:51:57.312 --> 00:52:00.192
They have to excel in school.
They have to excel in everything!

00:52:00.418 --> 00:52:03.698
Because if they get an A in Croatian,
or a B in Math,

00:52:04.050 --> 00:52:08.327
then the whole world has failed.
We expect too much from children.

00:52:08.525 --> 00:52:12.765
Sport has become too serious
and it’s too early to train.

00:52:13.045 --> 00:52:16.132
Not only that, there’s also
individual training.

00:52:16.306 --> 00:52:20.026
Everyone wants a piece of the pie.
Everyone wants to be part of it.

00:52:20.266 --> 00:52:24.106
And then there’s nutrition...
-But you don’t do sports for that?

00:52:24.505 --> 00:52:29.625
You ate bacon, onions...
Garlic, right?

00:52:30.140 --> 00:52:33.340
We ate whatever was offered.
-That’s right.

00:52:34.260 --> 00:52:36.820
Today’s kids have everything
at their fingertips

00:52:37.060 --> 00:52:42.780
and they have too much of everything.
We can’t expect them to be creative

00:52:43.020 --> 00:52:48.380
when everything’s handed to them.
They don’t have to think about anything.

00:52:48.487 --> 00:52:50.976
Before, when you traveled somewhere,
you had to have a map.

00:52:51.055 --> 00:52:53.518
You had to think about where
you were going and follow it.

00:52:53.682 --> 00:52:57.498
Now you sit in the car like a suitcase.
And you get from point A to point B.

00:52:57.672 --> 00:53:02.032
As for children and smartphones,
you’re right.

00:53:05.017 --> 00:53:12.183
They don’t need a phone at age six,
you’re right.

00:53:12.550 --> 00:53:16.777
But when they’re nine, ten, or eleven,
when they have friends...

00:53:16.878 --> 00:53:20.589
I’m not there yet. -You’re not,
but your kids will get there too.

00:53:21.100 --> 00:53:24.140
It’s hard to find a balance.

00:53:24.420 --> 00:53:26.721
You don’t want them to be
different from the others.

00:53:26.891 --> 00:53:29.251
Of course, I believe it’s hard.

00:53:29.352 --> 00:53:32.232
She wants to be part of the group,
part of the team. -Of course, it’s hard.

00:53:32.448 --> 00:53:36.010
But I guess it depends on your
relationship with your child. -Yes.

00:53:37.698 --> 00:53:45.784
How will you manage to gain your
child’s trust and have them trust you?

00:53:47.792 --> 00:53:52.323
That takes time and energy which
you have to devote, of course.

00:53:54.740 --> 00:54:04.039
You said that no Olympic medal
is as exhausting as raising children.

00:54:04.163 --> 00:54:08.586
Yes, motherhood.
-And that no day is the same. -Yes.

00:54:09.260 --> 00:54:19.295
As an athlete, everything is organized
for you to reach your full potential.

00:54:20.315 --> 00:54:23.526
One person carries one thing for you,
another person carries something else,

00:54:23.843 --> 00:54:27.349
you just have to bring your own things.

00:54:28.322 --> 00:54:31.587
You don’t even have to think
about what you’re going to eat.

00:54:31.948 --> 00:54:35.678
You only have to think
about basic needs.

00:54:35.990 --> 00:54:40.161
Going to the toilet and sleeping.
You don't think about anything else.

00:54:40.700 --> 00:54:43.820
Nobody interrupts you
in what you're doing.

00:54:44.260 --> 00:54:48.700
And this? It’s completely different.

00:54:50.220 --> 00:54:52.762
Every second, someone asks you
something, bothers you.

00:54:52.874 --> 00:54:55.809
You can't sleep when you want.
You can't do whatever you want...

00:54:56.276 --> 00:54:59.836
There's no continuity or rhythm.

00:55:00.204 --> 00:55:04.924
You never know how the child will react.
-Everything is a challenge?

00:55:05.126 --> 00:55:07.126
Everything is a challenge, literally.

00:55:07.414 --> 00:55:14.094
We're all parents, we're all moms,
and there's no drama there.

00:55:14.410 --> 00:55:16.370
But it's demanding.

00:55:17.705 --> 00:55:22.260
I can give my child a cell phone,
when I want to drink coffee in peace,

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:25.660
but I know it's not good for him.

00:55:27.225 --> 00:55:30.651
You don't do that, right?
-No, never. -Never? -Never.

00:55:30.915 --> 00:55:33.580
My children don’t have cell phones,
but they're still small.

00:55:33.718 --> 00:55:36.088
Seven and two years old.

00:55:36.740 --> 00:55:41.320
When you come to a restaurant
and want to eat something in peace,

00:55:41.628 --> 00:55:43.588
half an hour is enough...

00:55:43.817 --> 00:55:46.539
No, I'm the kind of mom
who runs around.

00:55:46.686 --> 00:55:51.992
And eats something along the way.
-Really? -Yes, and I’m catching the kids.

00:55:52.833 --> 00:55:59.485
Tell me, what you've learned from
sports, what has sports given you?

00:56:00.010 --> 00:56:01.250
What is it?

00:56:03.980 --> 00:56:06.220
A strong character.

00:56:07.420 --> 00:56:10.780
I don't know if it's sport
or a way of life?

00:56:12.136 --> 00:56:15.275
Sport definitely has an influence.

00:56:19.948 --> 00:56:26.963
After your career, you briefly
tried politics, right?

00:56:27.039 --> 00:56:28.846
Yes, that was in 2016.
-In your field.

00:56:28.949 --> 00:56:31.939
You were an advisor
to the Ministry of Sports.

00:56:32.388 --> 00:56:37.946
That's the first and only time you've
experienced some unpleasant moments.

00:56:38.999 --> 00:56:41.563
That's inevitable.
-I don't care about that.

00:56:41.683 --> 00:56:48.024
Does it bother you that society,
not just ours, is divided?

00:56:48.363 --> 00:56:57.894
It seems that the only chance to remain
like the heroine is to do nothing?

00:56:58.253 --> 00:56:59.410
Or to die?

00:57:01.174 --> 00:57:03.549
A person makes mistakes
when they work. -Too bad!

00:57:03.665 --> 00:57:07.964
Whatever you decide to do,
people will judge you.

00:57:16.302 --> 00:57:19.622
It's who says what, not what they say.
-Let's say that's the case.

00:57:20.001 --> 00:57:23.401
That was an interesting period.

00:57:24.540 --> 00:57:28.340
When I do something,
I try to do it conscientiously.

00:57:29.020 --> 00:57:31.500
But politics is strange.

00:57:32.620 --> 00:57:34.820
And it has nothing to do with sports.

00:57:34.954 --> 00:57:37.474
I thought politics shouldn't be
part of sports.

00:57:37.605 --> 00:57:43.685
But what disappointed me
the most were the many athletes,

00:57:43.909 --> 00:57:49.675
who I thought shared my views.

00:57:52.660 --> 00:57:59.860
Unfortunately, I've met few of them.
-That's too bad. That's good for you.

00:58:00.014 --> 00:58:04.024
But also for the country,
especially for the children,

00:58:04.163 --> 00:58:07.243
if they had such a person...

00:58:08.780 --> 00:58:12.620
It would be good if there
were no politics in sports.

00:58:12.860 --> 00:58:19.900
"Sports politics" could be
a special department at a university.

00:58:21.940 --> 00:58:24.660
Politics itself has no meaning.

00:58:25.377 --> 00:58:28.631
Literally, sometimes it's as if politics

00:58:28.713 --> 00:58:32.279
decides how many minutes
will be played in a match. -Yes.

00:58:33.034 --> 00:58:37.874
Or how many overtimes there will be.
How long the referee will allow extra time.

00:58:38.088 --> 00:58:43.646
Everyone thinks that if you give them
money, they'll get results.

00:58:45.020 --> 00:58:50.107
But results don’t come from money,
they come from hard work in training.

00:58:50.242 --> 00:58:53.155
That's what you should worry about,
not whether you received

00:58:53.271 --> 00:58:54.951
100 or 200 euros more or less.

00:58:55.090 --> 00:58:57.730
Politics and sports have
become a business,

00:58:57.821 --> 00:58:59.794
that's why they go hand in hand.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:06.251
Jana, we could talk for hours,
but it's best to stop,

00:59:06.365 --> 00:59:09.720
just like you stopped your career,
simply and gracefully.

00:59:09.829 --> 00:59:11.735
Thank you very much and goodbye.
-Thank you very much.

